<datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
<subfield code="a">Bible scholar and archaeologist William Fulco has been recruited to translate the screenplay of Mel Gibson's film The Passion from modern English into first-century Aramaic--the language Jesus spoke--and Latin (for the Roman characters).  The film, to be released in Easter 2004, promises to be Gibson's most ambitious, and certainly his most controversial to date:  a retelling of Jesus' last 12 hours, filmed entirely in the languages spoken in first-century Palestine.  For Fulco, translating the screenplay into the vernacular of first-century Palestine was no simple matter.  Although there are many examples of written Aramaic, there are precious few clues about what the spoken language actually sounded like in the first century, and consequently a certain degree of linguistic invention was required.</subfield>
</datafield>
